The US Anti-China Tech War
From New York — The worst foreign policy decision made by Americans of the previous generation (and even earlier generations) was the "war of choice" launched against Iraq in 2003, which claimed as its purpose the elimination — although they did not actually exist — of weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the flawed logic behind this catastrophic decision has become more important than ever, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar misleading US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then US Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was small (for example, 1 percent), we should act as if this situation would inevitably occur.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to wrong decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are currently using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot be sure that China's technology is safe, we should respond to it by treating it as necessarily harmful and banning it.
Proper decision-making would apply probability estimates to various alternative measures.
A generation ago, US policymakers should not only have considered the (alleged) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By emphasizing only that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) distracted the public's attention, causing people to neglect the fact that the Iraq War actually lacked legitimacy and would seriously undermine the political stability of the Middle East and the global political order.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it acts forcefully based on minor risks without considering the potentially high costs, but also that politicians always stoke fear for some ulterior motives.
This is exactly what American leaders are doing again: stoking panic about Chinese technology companies by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks.
The most relevant (but not the only) example is the attack by the U.S. government on the communications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and striving to kill its global business.
Just like in Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause a groundless geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological advancements closely, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide a significant driving force for poverty eradication and the achievement of other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and have encouraged the industry to enhance its actions towards the Sustainable Development Goals.
I wrote a short preface (without payment) for a report by Huawei on this topic, and therefore was criticized by those hostile to China. I asked senior industry figures and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in any inappropriate behavior, and repeatedly received the answer that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may harm global security.
U.S. officials claim that "backdoors" in Huawei's software or hardware could allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance worldwide.
They pointed out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But now the facts are right here.
Huawei's 5G equipment is affordable and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already begun to promote it.
Its high performance comes from massive investments in R&D over the years, economies of scale, and experience in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to their sustainable development, it would clearly be unwise for low-income economies around the world to refuse to roll out 5G early.
However, despite having no evidence of any backdoors, the United States is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The argument made by the United States is universal.
As one Federal Communications Commissioner in the United States said: "The country that has 5G will have the related innovation and set the standards for the rest of the world, and this country is currently unlikely to be the United States."
Other countries — especially the United Kingdom — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they can almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei is also heating up in Germany, as the US government threatens to cut intelligence cooperation unless the authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the US, the head of the German Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement reminiscent of Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a domain suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted."
However, he was unable to present any specific evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been quietly fighting to keep the market open to Huawei.
But ironically, the US's complaints actually partially reflect the US's own surveillance activities at home and abroad — although this is nothing new.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the US government to conduct secret surveillance.
However, any unjustified surveillance activities by any government should be stopped.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards, rather than engage in a technological war.
The threatening influence of the US demand to block Huawei is not limited to the early deployment of 5G networks, but also poses significant risks to the rule-based trading system.
Today, the United States is no longer the undisputed technological leader of the world, and President Donald Trump and his advisors do not want to compete according to a rules-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
At the same time, they are trying to destroy the WTO by paralyzing its dispute settlement mechanism, which also reflects their attitude toward the model of global rules.
If the Trump administration succeeds in "dividing" the world into different technological blocs, the risk of future conflicts will double.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency and expanded the US technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
The partial collapse was also due to protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression, contributed to the rise of Hitler, and ultimately pushed the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other areas, in the field of international affairs, inciting fear and acting on it — rather than acting on evidence — is a path to destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules, which is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring agencies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to monitor other countries or launch cyber wars.
This way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
